aving detailed migration inventory for later.\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"Does the proposed system-deep-loop structural layout preserve the current workflow/runtime split without creating ambiguous ownership or broken relative paths?\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"Structural layout should preserve workflows as public hub/mode packets and runtime as internal backend under a single system-deep-loop root.\"],\"ruledOut\":[{\"approach\":\"Flatten runtime and workflow packets into one directory\",\"reason\":\"Contradicts hub logic-free and runtime backend-only contracts.\",\"evidence\":\".opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/SKILL.md:37-39; .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/README.md:23-30\"}],\"toolsUsed\":[\"Read\",\"Glob\",\"Grep\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\".opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/SKILL.md:12\",\".opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/SKILL.md:72-85\",\".opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/mode-registry.json:1-17\",\".opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/README.md:23-30\",\".opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:819-859\"],\"graphEvents\":[{\"type\":\"node\",\"id\":\"q-structural-layout\",\"kind\":\"QUESTION\",\"label\":\"Structural layout preserves ownership seams\"},{\"type\":\"node\",\"id\":\"f-001-runtime-internal\",\"kind\":\"FINDING\",\"label\":\"Runtime remains internal backend under merged system\"},{\"type\":\"node\",\"id\":\"src-workflows-skill-12\",\"kind\":\"SOURCE\",\"label\":\"deep-loop-workflows hub contract\"},{\"type\":\"node\",\"id\":\"src-runtime-readme-23\",\"kind\":\"SOURCE\",\"label\":\"deep-loop-runtime README commandless backend contract\"},{\"type\":\"edge\",\"id\":\"... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"type\":\"iteration\",\"run\":2,\"iteration\":2,\"mode\":\"research\",\"target_agent\":\"deep-research\",\"agent_definition_loaded\":true,\"resolved_route\":\"Resolved route: mode=research target_agent=deep-research\",\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"Bidirectional path-coupling inventory\",\"focusTrack\":\"migration\",\"findingsCount\":7,\"newInfoRatio\":0.74,\"noveltyJustification\":\"This pass added a concrete migration surface taxonomy across command execution, generated contracts, doctor, agents, advisor, system-spec-kit, and runtime docs.\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"Which bidirectional path couplings between deep-loop-workflows, deep-loop-runtime, commands, agents, docs, tests, and scripts must be repaired mechanically during the merge?\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"Path-coupling repair must include command YAML and compiled contracts, doctor routes/assets, orchestrator/agents, advisor Python/TS/tests/metadata, system-spec-kit test/optimizer/docs, and runtime integration docs.\"],\"ruledOut\":[{\"approach\":\"Directory move without precomputed rewrite inventory\",\"reason\":\"Executable YAML, generated contracts, doctor routes, agents, advisor, and test config contain concrete old paths.\",\"evidence\":\".opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:64-77; .opencode/commands/doctor/_routes.yaml:100-110; .opencode/agents/orchestrate.md:180-206\"}],\"toolsUsed\":[\"Read\",\"Grep\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\".opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:64-77\",\".opencode/commands/deep/assets/compiled/deep_research.contract.md:1-80\",\".opencode/commands/doctor/_routes.yaml:100-110\",\".opencode/agents/orchestrate.md:180-206\",\".opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/scripts/skill_advisor.py:2570-2587\",\".opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/lib/scorer/aliases.ts:95-165\",\".opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/vitest.config.ts:15-22\",\".opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/optimizer/optimizer-manifest.json:7-18\",\".opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/references/integration_points.md:158-170\"],\"graphEvents\":[... (line truncated to 2000 chars)","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":4,"totalLines":4,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/052-deep-loop-unification/001-reference-research/research/lineages/gpt55-fast-1/deep-research-state.jsonl","time":{"start":1783487161288,"end":1783487161341}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09439ad4b1df9fb8016a4ddab93c44819183ecc432a454597d"}},"id":"prt_f401e63c6001ZftSz6Tf30EWV3","sessionID":"ses_0bfeb66caffeOOxX7Bbz2N0h6m","messageID":"msg_f401e0c58001q9VVs1rWAFK0VY"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783487161347,"sessionID":"ses_0bfeb66caffeOOxX7Bbz2N0h6m","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_ELVeeqKPUbG5TqoazqcnkiJL","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/052-deep-loop-unification/001-reference-research/research/lineages/gpt55-fast-1/iterations/iteration-002.md","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/052-deep-loop-unification/001-reference-research/research/lineages/gpt55-fast-1/iterations/iteration-002.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 2: Bidirectional Path-Coupling Inventory\n2: \n3: ## Focus\n4: This iteration inventoried concrete path couplings that a `deep-loop-runtime` + `deep-loop-workflows` merge must repair. The focus was not every textual mention, but migration-critical references that affect command execution, agent routing, test discovery, advisor routing, compiled command contracts, and operational diagnostics.\n5: \n6: ## Actions Taken\n7: - Read the current state log, strategy, and registry before selecting the path-coupling focus.\n8: - Grepped command, agent, advisor, and system-spec-kit surfaces for `deep-loop-runtime` and `deep-loop-workflows` references.\n9: - Read representative files at the highest-risk coupling points: `/deep:*` YAML contracts, doctor route manifest, orchestrator route contract, advisor deep-routing code, TypeScript alias projection, system-spec-kit test config, optimizer manifest, and runtime integration-points doc.\n10: \n11: ## Findings\n12: 1. `/deep:*` command YAML is the highest-risk rewrite surface because it embeds both sides of the split: mode packet paths under `deep-loop-workflows` and runtime script/library paths under `deep-loop-runtime`. `deep_research_auto.yaml` references workflow skill docs/assets [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:64-77], runtime fanout/lock/convergence/prompt/audit/validation/upsert/merge paths [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:160] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:229-243] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:616] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:819-859] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:1017-1039] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:1290-1297]. This must be migrated atomically with the directory move.\n13: 2. The compiled command contract is a second command-surface coupling, not just generated noise: `deep_research.contract.md` says it was generated by `deep-loop-runtime/scripts/compile-command-contracts.cjs` and carries source digests for `/deep:research`, both YAML modes, `mode-registry.json`, hub `SKILL.md`, and deep-research packet files [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/compiled/deep_research.contract.md:1-80]. Any path move must regenerate compiled contracts after source rewrites.\n14: 3. `/doctor deep-loop` directly routes diagnostics to runtime script paths and declares its route as read-only diagnostic over coverage/council graphs [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/doctor/_routes.yaml:100-110]. A merge must update doctor route manifests and doctor assets, or diagnostics will keep pointing to the old runtime skill.\n15: 4. Agent routing is coupled through `orchestrate.md`: deep routes must include a `Deep Route:` line whose source of truth is `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/mode-registry.json`, and dispatch correctness is verifiable by diffing against that registry [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/orchestrate.md:180-206]. The registry path is therefore an agent prompt contract, not just a documentation link.\n16: 5. The skill advisor has two hardcoded coupling layers. Python deep routing projects legacy deep skill IDs to `{skill: deep-loop-workflows, mode}` and sets `MODE_REGISTRY_PATH` to the workflows registry [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/scripts/skill_advisor.py:2570-2587]. TypeScript alias scoring similarly resolves old deep-loop aliases to `deep-loop-workflows` and points comments/readers to `deep-loop-workflows/mode-registry.json` [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/lib/scorer/aliases.ts:95-165]. Reference migration must include advisor source, tests, graph metadata, and generated skill graph records.\n17: 6. `system-spec-kit` is a bidirectional consumer, not only an external dependency. Its Vitest config discovers `../deep-loop-runtime/tests/**/*.{vitest,test}.ts` [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/vitest.config.ts:15-22], while its optimizer manifest lists deep-research/deep-review config files under `deep-loop-workflows` [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/optimizer/optimizer-manifest.json:7-18] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/optimizer/optimizer-manifest.json:30-39]. Moving either side without updating system-spec-kit tests and optimizer metadata will silently degrade verification.\n18: 7. The runtime integration-points document already records additional consumers beyond the main command loop: ai-council command/orchestration, doctor route/update, system-code-graph playbooks, legacy MCP READMEs, and deep-improvement docs [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/references/integration_points.md:158-170]. This is an existing migration checklist and should be used as a coverage oracle.\n19: \n20: ## Questions Answered\n21: - Answered: Bidirectional path-coupling repair must include command YAML + compiled contracts, doctor, agents, advisor Python/TS/tests/metadata, system-spec-kit test/optimizer/docs, runtime integration docs, and mode packet references.\n22: \n23: ## Questions Remaining\n24: - Which system-spec-kit tooling should remain borrowed rather than moved or duplicated?\n25: - What exact reference-migration plan is required for READMEs, catalogs, playbooks, and advisor corpus artifacts?\n26: - Whether fallback-router should be wired into real model fallback.\n27: \n28: ## Ruled Out\n29: - A pure `mv deep-loop-runtime deep-loop-workflows/runtime` without precomputed path rewrite is ruled out: executable YAML, command contracts, doctor routes, agent prompts, advisor scoring, and system-spec-kit tests all carry concrete old paths.\n30: \n31: ## Dead Ends\n32: - Relying on command contract generation alone to fix references is insufficient; contracts are generated outputs, but the source YAML, command markdown, advisor source, and test config also embed paths and must be updated first [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/compiled/deep_research.contract.md:1-80].\n33: \n34: ## Edge Cases\n35: - Ambiguous input: \"reference migration\" overlaps with \"path-coupling repair\"; this iteration classified executable and verification references as path-coupling, leaving prose docs/catalogs/playbooks for a later reference-migration pass.\n36: - Contradictory evidence: None found; sources consistently show both roots are currently live.\n37: - Missing dependencies: No code graph MCP was used; direct grep/read gave enough evidence.\n38: - Partial success: The coupling map is broad but not exhaustive at line-by-line scale; it identifies classes that need automated rewrite and validation.\n39: \n40: ## Sources Consulted\n41: - `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:64-77`\n42: - `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:160`\n43: - `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:229-243`\n44: - `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:616`\n45: - `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:819-859`\n46: - `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:1017-1039`\n47: - `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/compiled/deep_research.contract.md:1-80`\n48: - `.opencode/commands/doctor/_routes.yaml:100-110`\n49: - `.opencode/agents/orchestrate.md:180-206`\n50: - `.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/scripts/skill_advisor.py:2570-2587`\n51: - `.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/lib/scorer/aliases.ts:95-165`\n52: - `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/vitest.config.ts:15-22`\n53: - `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/optimizer/optimizer-manifest.json:7-18`\n54: - `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/references/integration_points.md:158-170`\n55: \n56: ## Assessment\n57: - New information ratio: 0.74\n58: - Novelty justification: This pass added a concrete migration surface taxonomy across command execution, generated contracts, doctor, agents, advisor, system-spec-kit, and runtime docs.\n59: - Questions addressed: path coupling; reference migration precursor; system-spec-kit interaction.\n60: - Questions answered: path coupling answered at class level with representative source anchors.\n61: - Confidence: High for the listed migration classes; medium for total occurrence count because the repo contains many catalog/playbook references intentionally left for iteration 4.\n62: \n63: ## Reflection\n64: - What worked and why: Searching exact old root names across scoped surfaces quickly exposed executable couplings.\n65: - What did not work and why: Global grep results included generated/corpus artifacts; classifying by runtime impact was necessary to avoid false priority.\n66: - What I would do differently: Separate executable path rewrites from documentation/corpus rewrite in the final migration plan.\n67: \n68: ## Recommended Next Focus\n69: System-spec-kit tooling borrow: identify which current shared pieces (`resolveArtifactRoot`, spec validation, memory/context save, resource-map extraction, optimizer/test discovery) should remain external contracts versus be moved, wrapped, or duplicated under the merged `system-deep-loop` root.\n\n(End of file - total 69 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 2: Bidirectional Path-Coupling Inventory\n\n## Focus\nThis iteration inventoried concrete path couplings that a `deep-loop-runtime` + `deep-loop-workflows` merge must repair. The focus was not every textual mention, but migration-critical references that affect command execution, agent routing, test discovery, advisor routing, compiled command contracts, and operational diagnostics.\n\n## Actions Taken\n- Read the current state log, strategy, and registry before selecting the path-coupling focus.\n- Grepped command, agent, advisor, and system-spec-kit surfaces for `deep-loop-runtime` and `deep-loop-workflows` references.\n- Read representative files at the highest-risk coupling points: `/deep:*` YAML contracts, doctor route manifest, orchestrator route contract, advisor deep-routing code, TypeScript alias projection, system-spec-kit test config, optimizer manifest, and runtime integration-points doc.\n\n## Findings\n1. `/deep:*` command YAML is the highest-risk rewrite surface because it embeds both sides of the split: mode packet paths under `deep-loop-workflows` and runtime script/library paths under `deep-loop-runtime`. `deep_research_auto.yaml` references workflow skill docs/assets [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:64-77], runtime fanout/lock/convergence/prompt/audit/validation/upsert/merge paths [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:160] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:229-243] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:616] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:819-859] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:1017-1039] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:1290-1297]. This must be migrated atomically with the directory move.\n2. The compiled command contract is a second command-surface coupling, not just generated noise: `deep_research.contract.md` says it was generated by `deep-loop-runtime/scripts/compile-command-contracts.cjs` and carries source digests for `/deep:research`, both YAML modes, `mode-registry.json`, hub `SKILL.md`, and deep-research packet files [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/compiled/deep_research.contract.md:1-80]. Any path move must regenerate compiled contracts after source rewrites.\n3. `/doctor deep-loop` directly routes diagnostics to runtime script paths and declares its route as read-only diagnostic over coverage/council graphs [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/doctor/_routes.yaml:100-110]. A merge must update doctor route manifests and doctor assets, or diagnostics will keep pointing to the old runtime skill.\n4. Agent routing is coupled through `orchestrate.md`: deep routes must include a `Deep Route:` line whose source of truth is `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/mode-registry.json`, and dispatch correctness is verifiable by diffing against that registry [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/orchestrate.md:180-206]. The registry path is therefore an agent prompt contract, not just a documentation link.\n5. The skill advisor has two hardcoded coupling layers. Python deep routing projects legacy deep skill IDs to `{skill: deep-loop-workflows, mode}` and sets `MODE_REGISTRY_PATH` to the workflows registry [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/scripts/skill_advisor.py:2570-2587]. TypeScript alias scoring similarly resolves old deep-loop aliases to `deep-loop-workflows` and points comments/readers to `deep-loop-workflows/mode-registry.json` [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/lib/scorer/aliases.ts:95-165]. Reference migration must include advisor source, tests, graph metadata, and generated skill graph records.\n6. `system-spec-kit` is a bidirectional consumer, not only an external dependency. Its Vitest config discovers `../deep-loop-runtime/tests/**/*.{vitest,test}.ts` [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/vitest.config.ts:15-22], while its optimizer manifest lists deep-research/deep-review config files under `deep-loop-workflows` [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/optimizer/optimizer-manifest.json:7-18] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/optimizer/optimizer-manifest.json:30-39]. Moving either side without updating system-spec-kit tests and optimizer metadata will silently degrade verification.\n7. The runtime integration-points document already records additional consumers beyond the main command loop: ai-council command/orchestration, doctor route/update, system-code-graph playbooks, legacy MCP READMEs, and deep-improvement docs [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/references/integration_points.md:158-170]. This is an existing migration checklist and should be used as a coverage oracle.\n\n## Questions Answered","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/052-deep-loop-unification/001-reference-research/research/lineages/gpt55-fast-1/iterations/iteration-002.md","text":"# Iteration 2: Bidirectional Path-Coupling Inventory\n\n## Focus\nThis iteration inventoried concrete path couplings that a `deep-loop-runtime` + `deep-loop-workflows` merge must repair. The focus was not every textual mention, but migration-critical references that affect command execution, agent routing, test discovery, advisor routing, compiled command contracts, and operational diagnostics.\n\n## Actions Taken\n- Read the current state log, strategy, and registry before selecting the path-coupling focus.\n- Grepped command, agent, advisor, and system-spec-kit surfaces for `deep-loop-runtime` and `deep-loop-workflows` references.\n- Read representative files at the highest-risk coupling points: `/deep:*` YAML contracts, doctor route manifest, orchestrator route contract, advisor deep-routing code, TypeScript alias projection, system-spec-kit test config, optimizer manifest, and runtime integration-points doc.\n\n## Findings\n1. `/deep:*` command YAML is the highest-risk rewrite surface because it embeds both sides of the split: mode packet paths under `deep-loop-workflows` and runtime script/library paths under `deep-loop-runtime`. `deep_research_auto.yaml` references workflow skill docs/assets [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:64-77], runtime fanout/lock/convergence/prompt/audit/validation/upsert/merge paths [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:160] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:229-243] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:616] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:819-859] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:1017-1039] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:1290-1297]. This must be migrated atomically with the directory move.\n2. The compiled command contract is a second command-surface coupling, not just generated noise: `deep_research.contract.md` says it was generated by `deep-loop-runtime/scripts/compile-command-contracts.cjs` and carries source digests for `/deep:research`, both YAML modes, `mode-registry.json`, hub `SKILL.md`, and deep-research packet files [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/compiled/deep_research.contract.md:1-80]. Any path move must regenerate compiled contracts after source rewrites.\n3. `/doctor deep-loop` directly routes diagnostics to runtime script paths and declares its route as read-only diagnostic over coverage/council graphs [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/doctor/_routes.yaml:100-110]. A merge must update doctor route manifests and doctor assets, or diagnostics will keep pointing to the old runtime skill.\n4. Agent routing is coupled through `orchestrate.md`: deep routes must include a `Deep Route:` line whose source of truth is `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/mode-registry.json`, and dispatch correctness is verifiable by diffing against that registry [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/orchestrate.md:180-206]. The registry path is therefore an agent prompt contract, not just a documentation link.\n5. The skill advisor has two hardcoded coupling layers. Python deep routing projects legacy deep skill IDs to `{skill: deep-loop-workflows, mode}` and sets `MODE_REGISTRY_PATH` to the workflows registry [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/scripts/skill_advisor.py:2570-2587]. TypeScript alias scoring similarly resolves old deep-loop aliases to `deep-loop-workflows` and points comments/readers to `deep-loop-workflows/mode-registry.json` [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/lib/scorer/aliases.ts:95-165]. Reference migration must include advisor source, tests, graph metadata, and generated skill graph records.\n6. `system-spec-kit` is a bidirectional consumer, not only an external dependency. Its Vitest config discovers `../deep-loop-runtime/tests/**/*.{vitest,test}.ts` [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/vitest.config.ts:15-22], while its optimizer manifest lists deep-research/deep-review config files under `deep-loop-workflows` [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/optimizer/optimizer-manifest.json:7-18] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/optimizer/optimizer-manifest.json:30-39]. Moving either side without updating system-spec-kit tests and optimizer metadata will silently degrade verification.\n7. The runtime integration-points document already records additional consumers beyond the main command loop: ai-council command/orchestration, doctor route/update, system-code-graph playbooks, legacy MCP READMEs, and deep-improvement docs [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/references/integration_points.md:158-170]. This is an existing migration checklist and should be used as a coverage oracle.\n\n## Questions Answered\n- Answered: Bidirectional path-coupling repair must include command YAML + compiled contracts, doctor, agents, advisor Python/TS/tests/metadata, system-spec-kit test/optimizer/docs, runtime integration docs, and mode packet references.\n\n## Questions Remaining\n- Which system-spec-kit tooling should remain borrowed rather than moved or duplicated?\n- What exact reference-migration plan is required for READMEs, catalogs, playbooks, and advisor corpus artifacts?\n- Whether fallback-router should be wired into real model fallback.\n\n## Ruled Out\n- A pure `mv deep-loop-runtime deep-loop-workflows/runtime` without precomputed path rewrite is ruled out: executable YAML, command contracts, doctor routes, agent prompts, advisor scoring, and system-spec-kit tests all carry concrete old paths.\n\n## Dead Ends\n- Relying on command contract generation alone to fix references is insufficient; contracts are generated outputs, but the source YAML, command markdown, advisor source, and test config also embed paths and must be updated first [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/compiled/deep_research.contract.md:1-80].\n\n## Edge Cases\n- Ambiguous input: \"reference migration\" overlaps with \"path-coupling repair\"; this iteration classified executable and verification references as path-coupling, leaving prose docs/catalogs/playbooks for a later reference-migration pass.\n- Contradictory evidence: None found; sources consistently show both roots are currently live.\n- Missing dependencies: No code graph MCP was used; direct grep/read gave enough evidence.\n- Partial success: The coupling map is broad but not exhaustive at line-by-line scale; it identifies classes that need automated rewrite and validation.\n\n## Sources Consulted\n- `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:64-77`\n- `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:160`\n- `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:229-243`\n- `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:616`\n- `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:819-859`\n- `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:1017-1039`\n- `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/compiled/deep_research.contract.md:1-80`\n- `.opencode/commands/doctor/_routes.yaml:100-110`\n- `.opencode/agents/orchestrate.md:180-206`\n- `.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/scripts/skill_advisor.py:2570-2587`\n- `.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/lib/scorer/aliases.ts:95-165`\n- `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/vitest.config.ts:15-22`\n- `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/optimizer/optimizer-manifest.json:7-18`\n- `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/references/integration_points.md:158-170`\n\n## Assessment\n- New information ratio: 0.74\n- Novelty justification: This pass added a concrete migration surface taxonomy across command execution, generated contracts, doctor, agents, advisor, system-spec-kit, and runtime docs.\n- Questions addressed: path coupling; reference migration precursor; system-spec-kit interaction.\n- Questions answered: path coupling answered at class level with representative source anchors.\n- Confidence: High for the listed migration classes; medium for total occurrence count because the repo contains many catalog/playbook references intentionally left for iteration 4.\n\n## Reflection\n- What worked and why: Searching exact old root names across scoped surfaces quickly exposed executable couplings.\n- What did not work and why: Global grep results included generated/corpus artifacts; classifying by runtime impact was necessary to avoid false priority.\n- What I would do differently: Separate executable path rewrites from documentation/corpus rewrite in the final migration plan.\n\n## Recommended Next Focus\nSystem-spec-kit tooling borrow: identify which current shared pieces (`resolveArtifactRoot`, spec validation, memory/context save, resource-map extraction, optimizer/test discovery) should remain external contracts versus be moved, wrapped, or duplicated under the merged `system-deep-loop` root.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":69,"totalLines":69,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/052-deep-loop-unification/001-reference-research/research/lineages/gpt55-fast-1/iterations/iteration-002.md","time":{"start":1783487161318,"end":1783487161345}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09439ad4b1df9fb8016a4ddab93c788191a864ee44b6a49259"}},"id":"prt_f401e63e4001IFNY9adTu4bECX","sessionID":"ses_0bfeb66caffeOOxX7Bbz2N0h6m","messageID":"msg_f401e0c58001q9VVs1rWAFK0VY"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783487161355,"sessionID":"ses_0bfeb66caffeOOxX7Bbz2N0h6m","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_QiemMmKt3c7wu4PemXY9VEZ5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/052-deep-loop-unification/001-reference-research/research/lineages/gpt55-fast-1/iterations/iteration-001.md","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/052-deep-loop-unification/001-reference-research/research/lineages/gpt55-fast-1/iterations/iteration-001.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 1: Structural Layout and Ownership Seams\n2: \n3: ## Focus\n4: This iteration verified the live relationship between `deep-loop-workflows`, `deep-loop-runtime`, and `/deep:*` command YAML before judging the proposed merge into `system-deep-loop`. The selected interpretation was structural ownership and public-surface preservation, not implementation mechanics.\n5: \n6: ## Actions Taken\n7: - Read the research lineage state files before research.\n8: - Read the `deep-loop-workflows` hub contract, mode registry, and README.\n9: - Read the `deep-loop-runtime` skill contract, README, library README, and integration-points reference.\n10: - Searched command YAML for runtime/workflow path references to test whether the split is only conceptual or actively coupled.\n11: \n12: ## Findings\n13: 1. The current architecture already expresses the desired future shape as a hub plus backend: `deep-loop-workflows` is the public advisor-routable skill and `deep-loop-runtime` is the frozen, MCP-free backend consumed by all active modes [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/SKILL.md:12]. This supports a merged `system-deep-loop` only if the merge preserves those two roles as distinct subdomains rather than flattening them.\n14: 2. The `deep-loop-workflows` layout is a parent hub with `mode-registry.json`, exactly one `graph-metadata.json`, four active mode packets, and `shared/synthesis/` helpers [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/SKILL.md:72-82]. The merge design should keep that as the user-facing layer, likely as `system-deep-loop/workflows/` or equivalent, not intermix mode packet docs with runtime libraries.\n15: 3. `mode-registry.json` is load-bearing because it binds `workflowMode`, `runtimeLoopType`, `backendKind`, packet, command, agent, aliases, and advisor projection data [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/mode-registry.json:1-17] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/mode-registry.json:29-53]. Any structural move must migrate this registry and its drift guards before or atomically with file-path rewrites.\n16: 4. `deep-loop-runtime` explicitly has no user-facing command or MCP tool surface; it is consumed through TypeScript imports and `.cjs` script calls [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/README.md:23-30] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/README.md:166-168]. In a merged system, runtime should remain an internal backend package, not another advisor-routable nested skill.\n17: 5. The runtime has three internal component families (`lib/deep-loop/`, `lib/coverage-graph/`, `lib/council/`) plus scripts and database ownership [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/README.md:88-103]. That argues for a structural layout that keeps runtime modules under a single stable root so `.cjs` scripts and TS imports are mechanically rewriteable.\n18: 6. `/deep:research` YAML currently calls both the workflow packet and runtime paths directly: it references the deep-research skill assets plus runtime scripts/libs for fan-out, lock, convergence, prompt-pack, audit, validation, graph upsert, and telemetry [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:64-77] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:819-859] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:1017-1039]. The merge cannot be just a directory move; command assets are primary migration targets.\n19: \n20: ## Questions Answered\n21: - Partially answered: structural layout should preserve `workflows` as the public hub/mode-packet layer and `runtime` as the internal backend layer under a single `system-deep-loop` root.\n22: \n23: ## Questions Remaining\n24: - Exact path-coupling inventory for commands, agents, docs, tests, scripts, and advisor corpus.\n25: - Which system-spec-kit tooling is borrowed versus duplicated.\n26: - Whether fallback-router should become active fallback wiring.\n27: \n28: ## Ruled Out\n29: - Flattening all mode packets and runtime modules into one directory is ruled out because the live contracts say the hub holds no per-mode logic and the runtime is an internal backend with no user command surface [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/SKILL.md:37-39] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/README.md:108-127].\n30: \n31: ## Dead Ends\n32: - Treating `deep-loop-runtime` as a separate user-facing skill after the merge is a dead end: its own README says it has no slash commands or MCP tools and works on one consumer skill [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/README.md:23-30].\n33: \n34: ## Edge Cases\n35: - Ambiguous input: The phrase \"folding deep-loop-runtime into deep-loop-workflows as system-deep-loop\" could mean physical nesting or logical unification. Evidence supports logical unification with nested internal runtime boundaries.\n36: - Contradictory evidence: None found in this iteration.\n37: - Missing dependencies: No prior `resource-map.md` existed in the spec folder, so this iteration used direct source reads and grep results.\n38: - Partial success: Structural direction is answered; the full path inventory remains for the next focus.\n39: \n40: ## Sources Consulted\n41: - `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/SKILL.md:12`\n42: - `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/SKILL.md:72-85`\n43: - `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/mode-registry.json:1-17`\n44: - `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/mode-registry.json:29-53`\n45: - `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/README.md:23-30`\n46: - `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/README.md:88-103`\n47: - `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:64-77`\n48: - `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:819-859`\n49: \n50: ## Assessment\n51: - New information ratio: 0.82\n52: - Novelty justification: First evidence pass surfaced the core structural invariant and showed that command YAML actively couples both skill roots, while leaving detailed migration inventory for later.\n53: - Questions addressed: structural layout; initial path-coupling context.\n54: - Questions answered: structural layout partially answered.\n55: - Confidence: High for ownership boundaries; medium for exact target directory names because implementation design is not in-scope to execute here.\n56: \n57: ## Reflection\n58: - What worked and why: Reading hub/runtime contracts first clarified ownership before getting lost in path inventories.\n59: - What did not work and why: Broad glob output was noisy because deep-loop-workflows contains large catalogs and playbooks; exact path searches will be better next.\n60: - What I would do differently: Use targeted grep against command/agent/docs/advisor surfaces in the next iteration.\n61: \n62: ## Recommended Next Focus\n63: Path-coupling inventory: enumerate concrete references to `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime` and `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows` across commands, agents, docs, scripts, tests, and advisor surfaces, and classify which must rewrite atomically for the merge.\n\n(End of file - total 63 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 1: Structural Layout and Ownership Seams\n\n## Focus\nThis iteration verified the live relationship between `deep-loop-workflows`, `deep-loop-runtime`, and `/deep:*` command YAML before judging the proposed merge into `system-deep-loop`. The selected interpretation was structural ownership and public-surface preservation, not implementation mechanics.\n\n## Actions Taken\n- Read the research lineage state files before research.\n- Read the `deep-loop-workflows` hub contract, mode registry, and README.\n- Read the `deep-loop-runtime` skill contract, README, library README, and integration-points reference.\n- Searched command YAML for runtime/workflow path references to test whether the split is only conceptual or actively coupled.\n\n## Findings\n1. The current architecture already expresses the desired future shape as a hub plus backend: `deep-loop-workflows` is the public advisor-routable skill and `deep-loop-runtime` is the frozen, MCP-free backend consumed by all active modes [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/SKILL.md:12]. This supports a merged `system-deep-loop` only if the merge preserves those two roles as distinct subdomains rather than flattening them.\n2. The `deep-loop-workflows` layout is a parent hub with `mode-registry.json`, exactly one `graph-metadata.json`, four active mode packets, and `shared/synthesis/` helpers [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/SKILL.md:72-82]. The merge design should keep that as the user-facing layer, likely as `system-deep-loop/workflows/` or equivalent, not intermix mode packet docs with runtime libraries.\n3. `mode-registry.json` is load-bearing because it binds `workflowMode`, `runtimeLoopType`, `backendKind`, packet, command, agent, aliases, and advisor projection data [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/mode-registry.json:1-17] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/mode-registry.json:29-53]. Any structural move must migrate this registry and its drift guards before or atomically with file-path rewrites.\n4. `deep-loop-runtime` explicitly has no user-facing command or MCP tool surface; it is consumed through TypeScript imports and `.cjs` script calls [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/README.md:23-30] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/README.md:166-168]. In a merged system, runtime should remain an internal backend package, not another advisor-routable nested skill.\n5. The runtime has three internal component families (`lib/deep-loop/`, `lib/coverage-graph/`, `lib/council/`) plus scripts and database ownership [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/README.md:88-103]. That argues for a structural layout that keeps runtime modules under a single stable root so `.cjs` scripts and TS imports are mechanically rewriteable.\n6. `/deep:research` YAML currently calls both the workflow packet and runtime paths directly: it references the deep-research skill assets plus runtime scripts/libs for fan-out, lock, convergence, prompt-pack, audit, validation, graph upsert, and telemetry [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:64-77] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:819-859] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:1017-1039]. The merge cannot be just a directory move; command assets are primary migration targets.\n\n## Questions Answered","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/052-deep-loop-unification/001-reference-research/research/lineages/gpt55-fast-1/iterations/iteration-001.md","text":"# Iteration 1: Structural Layout and Ownership Seams\n\n## Focus\nThis iteration verified the live relationship between `deep-loop-workflows`, `deep-loop-runtime`, and `/deep:*` command YAML before judging the proposed merge into `system-deep-loop`. The selected interpretation was structural ownership and public-surface preservation, not implementation mechanics.\n\n## Actions Taken\n- Read the research lineage state files before research.\n- Read the `deep-loop-workflows` hub contract, mode registry, and README.\n- Read the `deep-loop-runtime` skill contract, README, library README, and integration-points reference.\n- Searched command YAML for runtime/workflow path references to test whether the split is only conceptual or actively coupled.\n\n## Findings\n1. The current architecture already expresses the desired future shape as a hub plus backend: `deep-loop-workflows` is the public advisor-routable skill and `deep-loop-runtime` is the frozen, MCP-free backend consumed by all active modes [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/SKILL.md:12]. This supports a merged `system-deep-loop` only if the merge preserves those two roles as distinct subdomains rather than flattening them.\n2. The `deep-loop-workflows` layout is a parent hub with `mode-registry.json`, exactly one `graph-metadata.json`, four active mode packets, and `shared/synthesis/` helpers [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/SKILL.md:72-82]. The merge design should keep that as the user-facing layer, likely as `system-deep-loop/workflows/` or equivalent, not intermix mode packet docs with runtime libraries.\n3. `mode-registry.json` is load-bearing because it binds `workflowMode`, `runtimeLoopType`, `backendKind`, packet, command, agent, aliases, and advisor projection data [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/mode-registry.json:1-17] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/mode-registry.json:29-53]. Any structural move must migrate this registry and its drift guards before or atomically with file-path rewrites.\n4. `deep-loop-runtime` explicitly has no user-facing command or MCP tool surface; it is consumed through TypeScript imports and `.cjs` script calls [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/README.md:23-30] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/README.md:166-168]. In a merged system, runtime should remain an internal backend package, not another advisor-routable nested skill.\n5. The runtime has three internal component families (`lib/deep-loop/`, `lib/coverage-graph/`, `lib/council/`) plus scripts and database ownership [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/README.md:88-103]. That argues for a structural layout that keeps runtime modules under a single stable root so `.cjs` scripts and TS imports are mechanically rewriteable.\n6. `/deep:research` YAML currently calls both the workflow packet and runtime paths directly: it references the deep-research skill assets plus runtime scripts/libs for fan-out, lock, convergence, prompt-pack, audit, validation, graph upsert, and telemetry [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:64-77] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:819-859] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:1017-1039]. The merge cannot be just a directory move; command assets are primary migration targets.\n\n## Questions Answered\n- Partially answered: structural layout should preserve `workflows` as the public hub/mode-packet layer and `runtime` as the internal backend layer under a single `system-deep-loop` root.\n\n## Questions Remaining\n- Exact path-coupling inventory for commands, agents, docs, tests, scripts, and advisor corpus.\n- Which system-spec-kit tooling is borrowed versus duplicated.\n- Whether fallback-router should become active fallback wiring.\n\n## Ruled Out\n- Flattening all mode packets and runtime modules into one directory is ruled out because the live contracts say the hub holds no per-mode logic and the runtime is an internal backend with no user command surface [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/SKILL.md:37-39] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/README.md:108-127].\n\n## Dead Ends\n- Treating `deep-loop-runtime` as a separate user-facing skill after the merge is a dead end: its own README says it has no slash commands or MCP tools and works on one consumer skill [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/README.md:23-30].\n\n## Edge Cases\n- Ambiguous input: The phrase \"folding deep-loop-runtime into deep-loop-workflows as system-deep-loop\" could mean physical nesting or logical unification. Evidence supports logical unification with nested internal runtime boundaries.\n- Contradictory evidence: None found in this iteration.\n- Missing dependencies: No prior `resource-map.md` existed in the spec folder, so this iteration used direct source reads and grep results.\n- Partial success: Structural direction is answered; the full path inventory remains for the next focus.\n\n## Sources Consulted\n- `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/SKILL.md:12`\n- `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/SKILL.md:72-85`\n- `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/mode-registry.json:1-17`\n- `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/mode-registry.json:29-53`\n- `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/README.md:23-30`\n- `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/README.md:88-103`\n- `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:64-77`\n- `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_research_auto.yaml:819-859`\n\n## Assessment\n- New information ratio: 0.82\n- Novelty justification: First evidence pass surfaced the core structural invariant and showed that command YAML actively couples both skill roots, while leaving detailed migration inventory for later.\n- Questions addressed: structural layout; initial path-coupling context.\n- Questions answered: structural layout partially answered.\n- Confidence: High for ownership boundaries; medium for exact target directory names because implementation design is not in-scope to execute here.\n\n## Reflection\n- What worked and why: Reading hub/runtime contracts first clarified ownership before getting lost in path inventories.\n- What did not work and why: Broad glob output was noisy because deep-loop-workflows contains large catalogs and playbooks; exact path searches will be better next.\n- What I would do differently: Use targeted grep against command/agent/docs/advisor surfaces in the next iteration.\n\n## Recommended Next Focus\nPath-coupling inventory: enumerate concrete references to `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime` and `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows` across commands, agents, docs, scripts, tests, and advisor surfaces, and classify which must rewrite atomically for the merge.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":63,"totalLines":63,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/052-deep-loop-unification/001-reference-research/research/lineages/gpt55-fast-1/iterations/iteration-001.md","time":{"start":1783487161315,"end":1783487161353}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09439ad4b1df9fb8016a4ddab93c6c8191a87b24c5e1a81807"}},"id":"prt_f401e63e1001leuRIJxs0EdCHj","sessionID":"ses_0bfeb66caffeOOxX7Bbz2N0h6m","messageID":"msg_f401e0c58001q9VVs1rWAFK0VY"}}
